AB  - The United Nations World Climate Research Programme (WCRP) has started to prepare a new generation of global climate model experiments. However, the research community already has huge volumes of data of which we have only explored a small fraction. The data from climate simulations comprise a range of different phenomena with complex and interacting atmospheric, oceanic, cryospheric and land-surface processes (Flato et al 2011). The picture, however, is still far from complete and many questions remain unanswered. Some fundamental questions address the character and origin of uncertainties associated with climate model simulations. Another is how we can improve our understanding through further modelling efforts. We question whether information from climate model runs could be used more effectively, and how so-called ‘ensembles of opportunity’ should be interpreted. Future progress may be enhanced by improving statisticians’ involvement to introduce new methods for distilling information from large data volumes and to design “smarter” ensembles tailored to specific objectives.
