TY  - BOOK
TI  - Towards an Uncertainty Taxonomy for Epidemiological Models
AU  - Bevan, Luke
AU  - Milne, Gregory
AB  - Since the advent of the SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) pandemic, epidemiological modellers have provided critically important policy advice to governments and decision-makers. Epidemiological models have come to be used for epidemic tracking more intensively than ever before with urgent and emergent developments incorporated and with constant retraining of models on the latest data. Such work is, unavoidably and naturally, beset with uncertainty. In this paper we argue that, as of yet, the practice of uncertainty taxonomisation in policy-relevant epidemiology is pre-paradigmatic, without a settled conceptualisation of different kinds of uncertainty or a stable nomenclature. This paper considers and adapts ideas from other high-impact policy-relevant disciplines, such as climate science, to suggest ways in which the uncertainties within epidemiological models can be understood and categorised. It then reflects on best practices for model-based policy advice within this context and suggests routes forwards for robust model-based decision support.
