TI  - Enhancing Policy-Relevance without Burning Up or Burning Out: A Strategy for Scientists
AU  - Graffy, Elisabeth
AB  - ABSTRACT: The pragmatism of using science to forge policy appeals to both scientists and policymakers, yet numerous challenges to the implementation of this idea remain unresolved. These challenges may be heightened when policy decisions are needed to resolve contentious. The experiences of the USGS National Water Quality Assessment (NAWQA) Program illustrates the advantage of viewing opportunities for strategic engagement with the policy process in terms of five stages of the policy process itself. These stages include: 1) Raising issues, 2) Framing issues, 3) Focusing policy priorities, 4) Crafting and passing legislation, and 5) Implementing policy goals through regulations and programs. Clearer insight into the function of scientific information at each stage of the process helps scientists maintain a responsive and credible role in the policy process, regardless of the “heat” of a given issue. Indeed, this strategy helps scientists maintain policy-relevance with less risk of burning up or burning out in the process.
