TI  - Plague, the Printing Press, and Public Health in Seventeenth-Century London
AU  - Greenberg, Stephen
T2  - Huntington Library Quarterly
AB  - Abstract At a time when news and public information in general were the tightly held monopoly of the English government, one sort of information was made widely available to the general population: mortality figures from outbreaks of plague. Starting in 1603, the City of London took official steps to get such information into the hands of the people, both in London and beyond. Stephen Greenberg's article “Plague, the Printing Press, and Public Health in Seventeenth-Century London” examines the mechanism of that distribution, including some of the curious anomalies that arose when printers struggled with the new challenges of producing large numbers of weekly broadsides containing reliable statistical data.
